# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1913-detroit-tigers-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1894-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1894 throughout the world.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The **1900 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' first in the American League, which received recognition as a major league one year later in 1901.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in fourth place out of eight teams with a record of 71–67, 12+1⁄2 games behind Charles Comiskey's Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Outfielder Dick Harley led the team with a .325 batting average, 77 runs scored, and 47 stolen bases.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Sport McAllister led in slugging percentage (.383), and Frank Dillon led in extra-base hits (30).
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller led the team with a 19–9 win-loss record for a .679 win percentage.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Jack Cronin led in innings pitched (372) and strikeouts (121).
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Burns and George Stallings had spent large sums of money for "releases of star players" and had paid "major league salaries" to the majority of the players.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The **1901 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' 2nd season in Major League Baseball.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team was a charter member of the American League, which was originally formed as the minor-league Western League, of which it had also been a charter member.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in third place with a record or 74–61, 8+1⁄2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Most of Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park, with Sunday games played at Burns Park due to Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller (23–13) led the team in wins and was the Tigers' first 20-game winner.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] His performance headlined a strong pitching staff that had the third lowest ERA (3.30) in the American League.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Joe Yeager had an ERA of 2.61, for the second best Adjusted ERA+ in the AL, behind Cy Young.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The offense was not as strong however, scoring 741 runs – fifth among the eight teams in the league.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team's best hitters were shortstop Kid Elberfeld (.308 average) and center fielder Jimmy Barrett (.293 average; 110 runs).
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers had played their games at Bennett Park since 1896, but the graduation to a major league meant that there would now be games scheduled on Sundays, which was forbidden by Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] In order to avoid running afoul of this stricture, owner James D.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Burns built a ballpark on his own property in Springwells Township, Michigan just outside the Detroit city limits.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Named Burns Park, the Tigers would play their Sunday home games there for the 1901 and 1902 seasons.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] During the 1901 season, Detroit attracted 259,430 fans at home and 238,100 on the road, for a total of 447,428.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit ranked third behind Chicago and Boston in overall attendance.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] 1902 was the second year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the newly formed American League.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in seventh place with a record of 58–77 (.385), 30½ games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The 1902 Tigers were outscored by their opponents 657 runs to 566.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 189,469, sixth out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's blue laws prevented the Tigers from playing baseball at Bennett Park on Sundays.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] As a result, the Tigers played their Sunday home games for the season at Burns Park; a stadium constructed by owner James D.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1903-detroit-tigers-season] 1903 was the third year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the still-new American League.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1903-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in fifth place with a record or 65–71 (.478), 25 games behind the Boston Americans.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1903-detroit-tigers-season] The 1903 Tigers outscored their opponents 567 to 539.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1903-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 224,523, sixth out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] 1904 was the fourth year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the American League.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in seventh place with a record of 62–90 (.408), 32 games behind the Boston Americans.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] They played ten tie games, which is the major league record.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] The 1904 Tigers were outscored by their opponents 627 to 505.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 177,796, seventh out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] In the year before Ty Cobb's arrival, pitcher George Mullin had a higher batting average than any of the team's regulars at .290.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1905-detroit-tigers-season] 1905 was the fifth year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the American League.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1905-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in third place with a record of 79–74 (.516), 151⁄2 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1905-detroit-tigers-season] The 1905 Tigers posted a run differential of -97, the lowest ever by a team with a winning record, breaking the previous record of -81 held by the 1882 Detroit Wolverines; the Tigers lost 48 games by 3 or more runs.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1905-detroit-tigers-season] The 1905 Tigers were outscored by their opponents 602 to 512, the largest negative run differential ever for a Major League team with a winning record.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1905-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 193,384, eighth out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1913-detroit-tigers-season] The **1913 Detroit Tigers season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1913-detroit-tigers-season/1913-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished sixth in the American League with a record of 66–87, 30 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
